{"id":"1903.00911","submitter":"Arvind Saibaba","authors":"Arvind K. Saibaba","title":"Randomized Discrete Empirical Interpolation Method for Nonlinear Model\n  Reduction","comments":"27 pages, 8 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NA cs.NA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Discrete empirical interpolation method (DEIM) is a popular technique for\nnonlinear model reduction and it has two main ingredients: an interpolating\nbasis that is computed from a collection of snapshots of the solution and a set\nof indices which determine the nonlinear components to be simulated. The\ncomputation of these two ingredients dominates the overall cost of the DEIM\nalgorithm. To specifically address these two issues, we present randomized\nversions of the DEIM algorithm. There are three main contributions of this\npaper. First, we use randomized range finding algorithms to efficiently find an\napproximate DEIM basis. Second, we develop randomized subset selection tools,\nbased on leverage scores, to efficiently select the nonlinear components.\nThird, we develop several theoretical results that quantify the accuracy of the\nrandomization on the DEIM approximation. We also present numerical experiments\nthat demonstrate the benefits of the proposed algorithms.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 3 Mar 2019 13:45:44 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 21 May 2019 13:34:16 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 26 Mar 2020 12:59:33 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-03-27"}
